{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Eyva9ezhSk5RKeDmCc5dwg","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## Implementation Checklist\n     2→- [ ] 1. Read `.ralph/specs/09-ansible-agent.md`, shared-library/refactor docs, and existing agent patterns to lock contract assumptions.\n     3→- [ ] 2. Create `skills/ansible-agent/scripts/ansible-agent.sh` with shared-lib sourcing, standard header, and agent-specific knobs.\n     4→- [ ] 3. Implement playbook discovery that supports no-arg auto-discovery and `CHANGED_FILES` filtering with deterministic host-key syntax prefilter.\n     5→- [ ] 4. Implement `run_lint` with CI-aware `FMT_MODE` and per-mode `ansible-lint` invocation (`check` default, `fix` local) plus robust logging.\n     6→- [ ] 5. Implement `run_syntax` over discovered playbooks with `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` and explicit file-level failure aggregation.\n     7→- [ ] 6. Implement CLI parser (`--help`, `-h`, `help`, `--fail-fast`), command dispatch (`lint`, `syntax`, `all`), and `RUN_*` gating/flow semantics.\n     8→- [ ] 7. Add scenario fixtures for clean, issues, command-specific behavior, and CHANGED_FILES/no-match coverage under `tests/ansible-agent/`.\n     9→- [ ] 8. Author `skills/ansible-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger language and allowed-tools including `FMT_MODE=*`, `RUN_*`, `CHANGED_FILES=*`, and `TMPDIR_ROOT=*`.\n    10→- [ ] 9. Update `install.sh` for `ansible-agent` SKILLS registration, optional dependency messaging, and AGENTS/CLAUDE snippet wording.\n    11→- [ ] 10. Update `README.md` with ansible-agent table entry and usage examples for `lint`, `syntax`, and `all`.\n    12→- [ ] 11. Run `tests/run-scenarios.sh ansible-agent` with clean/issues/fixture matrix and validate `shellcheck --severity=warning` passes.\n    13→- [ ] 12. Run `ralph validate plan` and fix any plan-format or sequence issues.\n    14→- [ ] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n    15→- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n    16→\n    17→## Architecture Review\n    18→\n    19→### System Design and Component Boundaries\n    20→- The ansible-agent remains a thin orchestration shell around two command steps (`lint`, `syntax`) and is invoked directly by `run-scenarios.sh` fixtures.\n    21→- Shared behavior (`step`, `print_result`, `setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, `need`, etc.) comes from `lib/x-agent-common.sh`; ansible-agent contributes only domain-specific discovery and command execution.\n    22→- The script boundary is: `run-scenarios.sh` -> ansible-agent -> local CLI tools (`ansible-lint`, `ansible-playbook`) -> filesystem reads + OUTDIR logs.\n    23→- External integration points are minimal: `install.sh` for discoverability and `README.md` for user contract; no runtime service calls.\n    24→\n    25→### Dependency Graph and Coupling\n    26→- Required runtime deps: `ansible-lint` and `ansible-playbook` (`need`-guarded and checked before running steps).\n    27→- Shared lib coupling is critical: changes to `x-agent-common.sh` (especially `need`, `print_result`, lock logic) impact all agents and should remain backward-compatible.\n    28→- Test coupling is through `.env` contract keys consumed by the harness (`SCENARIO_NAME`, `AGENT_SCRIPT`, `EXPECT_EXIT`, `REQUIRED_TOOLS`, `RUN_ARGS`, optional `CHANGED_FILES`).\n    29→- UI coupling via `SKILL.md` and README influences agent discoverability and automation matching quality.\n    30→\n    31→### Data Flow and Bottlenecks\n    32→- Flow: parse CLI/help/flags -> set defaults -> source/discover tool availability -> initialize output dir + lock -> resolve mode/targets -> execute command(s) -> write per-step logs -> print Step/Result/Fix/Overall.\n    33→- CHANGED_FILES affects two branches differently: scope decision for syntax-check targets and skip decision for lint run availability.\n    34→- Primary runtime bottlenecks: recursive YAML discovery (`find`) and per-playbook `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` execution in large repos.\n    35→\n    36→### Scaling Characteristics and Single Points of Failure\n    37→- In monorepos, recursive discovery dominates; prune rules are needed to avoid scanning binaries/node_modules equivalents.\n    38→- Single points of failure: missing required tools (`need` -> exit 2), no playbook discovery (`SKIP` path), malformed YAML causing syntax-check exits, or corrupted lock/temp directory handling.\n    39→- Locking in shared lib avoids concurrent tempdir/log interference but does not prevent command-level contention of ansible tooling.\n    40→\n    41→### Security Architecture\n    42→- No remote auth/API boundaries are introduced.\n    43→- Main attack surface is filesystem path handling and shell command execution; use guarded file filtering and quoting to prevent globbing issues.\n    44→- Running `ansible-lint --fix` locally is mutating by design; CI must force check mode and keep mutation-free behavior.\n    45→\n    46→### Key Architectural Decisions\n    47→\n    48→Decision 1: Playbook discovery model\n    49→- Option A (recommended): recursive `.yml/.yaml` candidate scan + filename heuristics + standard directories + optional `hosts:` filter for syntax candidates.\n    50→- Option B: only `ansible-lint --list`/CLI-discovered paths (simpler, lower control over scoped syntax path mapping).\n    51→- Option C: parse YAML safely with external parsers (`yq`, `python`) to infer playbook structure (accurate but adds dependencies and complexity).\n    52→- Chosen: Option A.\n    53→- Why: deterministic, fast enough for repo-scale fixture patterns, and consistent with existing agents' discovery style.\n    54→- Future impact: this heuristic can be reused for sql/kube-like agents needing mixed path+content rules.\n    55→\n    56→Decision 2: Scope semantics for lint vs syntax under `CHANGED_FILES`\n    57→- Option A (spec-compliant, recommended): syntax is scoped to changed playbook files; lint runs project-wide, but with scoped skip if no relevant YAML changed.\n    58→- Option B: scope lint to changed files only.\n    59→- Option C: scope lint to changed files only for changed-only mode and all files otherwise.\n    60→- Chosen: Option A.\n    61→- Why: matches FR-3/CHANGED behavior and avoids false negatives from partial lint decisions.\n    62→- Future impact: keeps parity with multi-step agents where expensive/cheap steps can have different scope semantics.\n    63→\n    64→Decision 3: FMT_MODE handling\n    65→- Option A (recommended): normalize `FMT_MODE` once in `resolve_fmt_mode` (`auto` -> `fix` local, `check` in CI).\n    66→- Option B: call `ansible-lint --fix` always and skip CI override.\n    67→- Option C: only `check|fix` allowed, no CI override.\n    68→- Chosen: Option A.\n    69→- Why: aligns with go-agent/terra-agent conventions and FR-10.\n    70→- Future impact: low-friction upgrade path for future agents needing local auto-fix semantics.\n    71→\n    72→## Code Quality Planning\n    73→\n    74→### Organization and Module Structure\n    75→- Keep file small and domain-specific (~<200 lines): discovery helpers, mode resolution, two step runners, and one CLI main entrypoint.\n    76→- Group variables in top block: universal knobs, agent knobs, and usage metadata.\n    77→- Keep `usage()` and `collect_playbooks` simple and testable by fixture output.\n    78→\n    79→### DRY Opportunities and Repetition Risk\n    80→- Reuse `print_result` and common timing/cleanup behavior from shared lib instead of custom equivalents.\n    81→- Centralize shared skip branch text in small helper constants if needed (`skip_no_targets`, `skip_no_syntax_targets`) to avoid copy drift.\n    82→- Use one discovery path variable and share filtering operations to prevent duplicated extension checks.\n    83→\n    84→### Error Handling Patterns (Explicit)\n    85→- `need ansible-lint` and `need ansible-playbook` happen before execution to fail fast with code 2.\n    86→- `resolve_fmt_mode` validates unsupported values and exits 2 with actionable message.\n    87→- Discovery functions emit explicit zero-target reasons and return success (no crash), letting caller generate deterministic `SKIP`.\n    88→- Command runners capture command exit codes, dump full output to logs, and only print truncated tails on failures.\n    89→- `main` maps unknown commands to usage + exit 2.\n    90→\n    91→### Technical Debt Controls\n    92→- Avoid clever parsing of YAML; use conservative heuristics with explicit limitations documented in usage and SKILL.\n    93→- Keep command args in arrays where practical; avoid broad global state and deeply nested logic.\n    94→- Add explicit fixture coverage for every branch with `CHANGED_FILES`, `all`, and command-specific invocation.\n    95→- Prefer plain POSIX/Bash 3.2 constructs (no associative arrays/readarray/\n    96→  shell features outside compatibility bounds).\n    97→\n    98→### Engineering Level\n    99→- Engineered enough: explicit branching for scope and modes, not over-abstracted.\n   100→- Avoid over-engineering by not adding config files, caching services, or language parsers unless future iterations need richer semantics.\n   101→\n   102→## Test Strategy\n   103→\n   104→### Coverage Plan\n   105→- Unit-like validation (script-level behavior)\n   106→  - `bash -n` syntax on script and shellcheck severity warning checks in harness.\n   107→- Integration (scenario-based)\n   108→  - `tests/run-scenarios.sh ansible-agent` as the canonical acceptance harness.\n   109→- End-to-end contract checks\n   110→  - Validate `install.sh` registration and README/Skill discoverability by running scenario coverage and grepping for required references.\n   111→\n   112→### Required Edge Cases + Fixture/Assertion Mapping\n   113→1. **Clean pass path**: `tests/ansible-agent/clean/` with valid playbook and required tools. Expect exit 0.\n   114→2. **Issues fail path**: `tests/ansible-agent/issues/` with lint violations. Expect exit 1 and `Fix:` present.\n   115→3. **All command default path**: `RUN_ARGS=\"all\"` on clean and issues fixtures.\n   116→4. **Lint-only command**: `RUN_ARGS=\"lint\"` on clean/issues; confirms command dispatch and `lint` message/fix hint.\n   117→5. **Syntax-only command**: `RUN_ARGS=\"syntax\"` with valid playbook + invalid syntax fixture to verify syntax discovery and aggregate behavior.\n   118→6. **CHANGED_FILES match (lint)**: export one valid playbook in `CHANGED_FILES`; expect lint step execute and overall pass/fail according fixture.\n   119→7. **CHANGED_FILES match (syntax)**: same but with `RUN_ARGS=\"syntax\"`; expect only changed playbooks syntax-checked.\n   120→8. **CHANGED_FILES no-match**: export non-YAML or non-playbook paths; expect `Result: SKIP (no playbooks ... CHANGED_FILES)` and exit 0.\n   121→9. **No playbooks discovered**: fixture with only non-playbook YAML or no YAML files; all commands should `SKIP` gracefully with exit 0.\n   122→10. **FMT_MODE local fix branch**: `FMT_MODE=fix` in clean/issues fixture with local env; ensure command switches to `ansible-lint --fix`.\n   123→11. **CI forces check**: `CI=true FMT_MODE=fix` still executes check mode; fail path should still emit lint SKIP/Fix guidance for check mode.\n   124→12. **Tool failure path (manual)**: invoke script where `ansible-lint` missing to confirm exit 2 (via direct call or environment without tool, since harness marks missing as `SKIP`).\n   125→\n   126→### Failure Modes and Error Path Testing\n   127→- Missing required binary -> exit 2 and clear `Missing required tool` message.\n   128→- Discovery misses files with scoped input -> SKIP path, code 0.\n   129→- ansible-lint returns error -> code 1 and fix hints with exact `/ansible-agent lint` command.\n   130→- ansible-playbook syntax failure -> code 1 with per-path logs and fix hint `/ansible-agent syntax`.\n   131→- Invalid `FMT_MODE` -> code 2 with explicit input guidance.\n   132→\n   133→### Assertion Strength\n   134→- Validate both exit status and branch intent in scenario labels/messages:\n   135→  - `Result: SKIP` vs `Result: PASS/FAIL`\n   136→  - Fix hint content includes exact command path (`/ansible-agent lint`, `/ansible-agent syntax`).\n   137→- For non-empty failure cases, assert full log generation path appears in output.\n   138→\n   139→## Performance Considerations\n   140→\n   141→### N+1 and Command Cost\n   142→- Avoid recomputing discovery for both steps; compute once per run and reuse in `all`.\n   143→- Do not call `find` per playbook. One repository scan + per-target syntax calls is the upper bound.\n   144→- Prefer one `ansible-lint` invocation for lint step vs repeated per-file invocation.\n   145→\n   146→### Memory Usage\n   147→- Store candidate paths in newline-separated strings or Bash arrays only as needed; avoid reading full file contents.\n   148→- Keep full diagnostics in disk logs under `OUTDIR`; avoid loading huge logs into memory.\n   149→\n   150→### Caching Opportunities\n   151→- Cache discovery output for current invocation in environment variable(s) (`PLAYBOOKS`, `CHANGED_PLAYBOOKS`).\n   152→- No cross-run cache; stale discovery state across changing worktrees is riskier than repeated scans.\n   153→\n   154→### Slow/Complex Paths\n   155→- Syntax-check is O(n files) process spawn overhead; this is expected and can be heavy for monorepos.\n   156→- `ansible-lint --fix` can be expensive and mutating; keep this local-only and CI check-only.\n   157→\n   158→### Performance Monitoring\n   159→- If ansible repos become large, prioritize adding prune paths (e.g., `.venv`, `.git`, `.cache`) and optionally role/playbook root detection to limit initial scan depth.\n   160→\n   161→## Decision Log\n   162→\n   163→- Decision: Use `ansible-lint` for lint and `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` for syntax with shared skip semantics\n   164→  - Options considered:\n   165→    - A) Dedicated ansible parser + custom checks.\n   166→    - B) `ansible-lint` + `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` with heuristic discovery.\n   167→    - C) Single command strategy using only `ansible-lint`.\n   168→  - Chosen approach: B.\n   169→  - Implications: clear separation of semantic concerns and predictable error messages across commands.\n   170→\n   171→- Decision: Keep syntax discovery stricter than lint discovery\n   172→  - Options considered:\n   173→    - A) Same target set for lint and syntax.\n   174→    - B) Syntax only runs files with explicit `hosts:` after YAML discovery.\n   175→    - C) Syntax uses lint-only target set.\n   176→  - Chosen approach: B.\n   177→  - Implications: reduces false syntax-check attempts on non-playbook YAML files and lowers avoidable command failures.\n   178→\n   179→- Decision: Keep install/docs as required spec output artifacts, not optional\n   180→  - Options considered:\n   181→    - A) Add script+fixtures only.\n   182→    - B) Add script/fixtures + install/README.\n   183→    - C) Add docs and install updates in separate follow-up.\n   184→  - Chosen approach: B.\n   185→  - Implications: operator and automation discoverability remains accurate immediately after implementation.\n   186→\n   187→## Edge Cases and Risks\n   188→- `CHANGED_FILES` contains spaces: shell word-splitting is path-sensitive; use tested patterns and document limitation.\n   189→- `CHANGED_FILES` includes only role helpers/templates without play-level hosts: syntax may skip while lint still executes.\n   190→- `ansible-lint --fix` may rewrite files; plan for fixture cleanup in manual run scripts if local mutation is tested.\n   191→- Syntax checking on large playbook trees can become slow; keep default `all` command path optimized with cached discovery.\n   192→- `ansible-playbook` on some enterprise collections may attempt optional dependencies; fixture design should avoid unavailable collection imports.\n   193→- `Need` checks can block execution in CI if tools are absent; fixture `REQUIRED_TOOLS` should stay explicit.\n   194→- Script output should preserve Step/Result/Fix/Overall contract even when SKIP paths occur.\n   195→\n   196→## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n   197→\n   198→### 1. Contract lock-in and dependency mapping\n   199→**What**: Read spec/standards and finalize exact behavior contract for lint/syntax/CHANGED/FMT_MODE.\n   200→**Why**: Prevents drift from FRs and prior agent conventions.\n   201→**How**:\n   202→- Review `.ralph/specs/09-ansible-agent.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `.ralph/specs/01-02`, and existing scripts (`docker/go/gha` style).\n   203→- Confirm command outputs, SKIP semantics, and required knobs.\n   204→**Edge Cases**:\n   205→- Misaligned FMT_MODE expectation.\n   206→- Confusion around when lint is skipped for scoped input.\n   207→**Tests**: none.\n   208→**Risks**: Early misunderstanding causing repeated fixture churn.\n   209→\n   210→### 2. Build ansible-agent script skeleton and shared-lib wiring\n   211→**What**: Create `skills/ansible-agent/scripts/ansible-agent.sh` with shebang, `set -euo pipefail`, shared lib source, and knob defaults.\n   212→**Why**: Establishes consistent runtime behavior and keeps boilerplate under control.\n   213→**How**:\n   214→- Add `SCRIPT_DIR`, `LIB_DIR`, `source` lines and shebang.\n   215→- Set `RUN_LINT`, `RUN_SYNTAX`, `FMT_MODE`, universal defaults.\n   216→- Keep script executable and named conventionally.\n   217→**Edge Cases**: `source` path errors if script moved; rely on `$(cd ...)` path normalization.\n   218→**Tests**: `shellcheck` catches missing path directives.\n   219→**Risks**: None.\n   220→\n   221→### 3. Implement `resolve_fmt_mode` and discovery helpers\n   222→**What**: Implement CI-aware mode resolver and helper functions for candidate detection.\n   223→**Why**: Centralizes behavior and avoids spread conditionals in runners.\n   224→**How**:\n   225→- `resolve_fmt_mode`: `auto -> local fix, CI check`; invalid mode -> exit 2.\n   226→- `collect_ansible_files`: gather existing `.yml/.yaml` files from `CHANGED_FILES` when set.\n   227→- `discover_playbooks`: recurse for filenames and role/playbook directories per spec; parse only files with `hosts:` for syntax list.\n   228→- Log how many matches were found.\n   229→**Edge Cases**:\n   230→- CHANGED_FILES includes non-existing files.\n   231→- No files found in repo scan.\n   232→- Commented `hosts:` lines not used for syntax selection.\n   233→**Tests**: scoped/ no-match fixtures.\n   234→**Risks**: Overly strict `hosts:` filter skipping valid playbooks with nonstandard layout.\n   235→\n   236→### 4. Implement `run_lint` with project-wide checks and local/CI mode behavior\n   237→**What**: Add lint step using `ansible-lint`.\n   238→**Why**: Core requested linting functionality with fixed/mutating modes.\n   239→**How**:\n   240→- If CHANGED_FILES exists and no `.yml/.yaml` are relevant, emit SKIP.\n   241→- Else call `ansible-lint` with no positional arguments for full project discovery, using `--fix` only in local fix mode.\n   242→- Log output and emit `/ansible-agent lint` fix hint variations for check vs fix failures.\n   243→**Edge Cases**:\n   244→- `ansible-lint --fix` may modify files; run in local branches only.\n   245→- Lint may fail due syntax/parser errors in changed fixtures.\n   246→**Tests**: clean/issues, lint-only mode, FMT_MODE fix and CI check forced path.\n   247→**Risks**: Tool output volume; ensure `MAX_LINES` truncation and full log path.\n   248→\n   249→### 5. Implement `run_syntax` over syntax-discovered targets\n   250→**What**: Add syntax step with `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` per playbook.\n   251→**Why**: Provides execution validation not covered by lint.\n   252→**How**:\n   253→- Iterate over `PLAYBOOKS_FOR_SYNTAX` list, run syntax-check per file into one log.\n   254→- On failures, track aggregate exit and print failing output slices.\n   255→- Return `SKIP` when no matching syntax targets.\n   256→**Edge Cases**:\n   257→- CHANGED_FILES empty + no syntax candidates.\n   258→- One target failing should fail whole step but still run no more files after? (decide fail-fast behavior is per-step only).\n   259→**Tests**: syntax-only pass/fail fixture.\n   260→**Risks**: Additional process overhead in large trees; acceptable with shared cache and path filters.\n   261→\n   262→### 6. Implement command dispatch and all-mode orchestration\n   263→**What**: Add parser for help, fail-fast, and command routing.\n   264→**Why**: Ensures compatibility with existing usage contract.\n   265→**How**:\n   266→- Parse `-h|--help|help` before `need` checks.\n   267→- Parse `--fail-fast` and set `FAIL_FAST`.\n   268→- `all` runs `run_lint` then `run_syntax` based on `RUN_*` with `should_continue`.\n   269→- Unknown command prints usage and exits 2.\n   270→**Edge Cases**:\n   271→- Extra positional args should be ignored or treated as unknown command deterministically.\n   272→**Tests**: invocation matrix for `lint`, `syntax`, `all`, unknown command.\n   273→**Risks**: Shift handling with positional args and default values.\n   274→\n   275→### 7. Add command/behavior fixtures\n   276→**What**: Create `tests/ansible-agent/*` clean/issues plus scoped command scenarios.\n   277→**Why**: Prevents regressions in command and CHANGED_FILES behavior.\n   278→**How**:\n   279→- Create `tests/ansible-agent/clean/` with valid `playbook.yml` and required tools.\n   280→- Create `tests/ansible-agent/issues/` with lint violations.\n   281→- Add at least one scoped-match and one scoped-no-match scenario env using exported `CHANGED_FILES`.\n   282→- Add syntax fixture set for command dispatch and syntax-only failures.\n   283→**Edge Cases**:\n   284→- Ensure variables requiring subprocess visibility are exported.\n   285→- Keep fixtures minimal and deterministic.\n   286→**Tests**: `tests/run-scenarios.sh ansible-agent` must cover these scenarios.\n   287→**Risks**: Overfitting fixtures to one environment or ansible version.\n   288→\n   289→### 8. Add SKILL.md for automation interoperability\n   290→**What**: Create `skills/ansible-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger phrases and allowed-tools.\n   291→**Why**: Required for install/agent integration and allowed tool discovery.\n   292→**How**:\n   293→- Use same structure as other agents.\n   294→- Include `RUN_LINT=*`, `RUN_SYNTAX=*`, `FMT_MODE=*`, `CHANGED_FILES=*`, `MAX_LINES=*`, `KEEP_DIR=*`, `FAIL_FAST=*`, `TMPDIR_ROOT=*`.\n   295→- Mention command forms `lint`, `syntax`, `all` and FMT guidance.\n   296→**Edge Cases**: Missing allowed-tools for `TMPDIR_ROOT` will break automation suggestions.\n   297→**Tests**: Manual read + grep checks.\n   298→**Risks**: Drift if allowed-tools not aligned to runtime knobs.\n   299→\n   300→### 9. Wire install and usage docs\n   301→**What**: Update `install.sh` and `README.md`.\n   302→**Why**: Required for user-facing discoverability and end-user installation path.\n   303→**How**:\n   304→- Add `ansible-agent` to `SKILLS` list and optional dependency check messaging.\n   305→- Extend snippet text in `print_agents_md_snippet` with ansible usage line.\n   306→- Add ansible row in README table and usage examples for lint/syntax commands.\n   307→**Edge Cases**: keep ordering and markdown formatting stable.\n   308→**Tests**: inspect generated snippet text via dry-run path or static diff.\n   309→**Risks**: inconsistent skill naming breaks installer selection.\n   310→\n   311→### 10. Verification and gating\n   312→**What**: Execute required checks and close plan.\n   313→**Why**: Confirms all quality gates before handoff.\n   314→**How**:\n   315→- Run `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/ansible-agent/scripts/ansible-agent.sh lib/x-agent-common.sh tests/run-scenarios.sh`.\n   316→- Run `tests/run-scenarios.sh ansible-agent`.\n   317→- Run `ralph validate plan`.\n   318→- Update `.ralph/exploration.md` with ansible-specific discoveries if files/patterns changed.\n   319→- Run `ralph validate work` and stop on PASS.\n   320→**Edge Cases**: command-specific fixture expectations may fail due path formatting differences.\n   321→**Tests**: explicit commands above.\n   322→**Risks**: validation tooling may require exact checklist ordering and item order.\n   323→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"32a521e9-fb0e-42cc-9cbd-d9c4ff505402","uuid":"0ffcd230-ba98-4e45-8107-0404a42e3315","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/chrisraethke/projects/x-agent/.ralph/work-plan.txt","content":"## Implementation Checklist\n- [ ] 1. Read `.ralph/specs/09-ansible-agent.md`, shared-library/refactor docs, and existing agent patterns to lock contract assumptions.\n- [ ] 2. Create `skills/ansible-agent/scripts/ansible-agent.sh` with shared-lib sourcing, standard header, and agent-specific knobs.\n- [ ] 3. Implement playbook discovery that supports no-arg auto-discovery and `CHANGED_FILES` filtering with deterministic host-key syntax prefilter.\n- [ ] 4. Implement `run_lint` with CI-aware `FMT_MODE` and per-mode `ansible-lint` invocation (`check` default, `fix` local) plus robust logging.\n- [ ] 5. Implement `run_syntax` over discovered playbooks with `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` and explicit file-level failure aggregation.\n- [ ] 6. Implement CLI parser (`--help`, `-h`, `help`, `--fail-fast`), command dispatch (`lint`, `syntax`, `all`), and `RUN_*` gating/flow semantics.\n- [ ] 7. Add scenario fixtures for clean, issues, command-specific behavior, and CHANGED_FILES/no-match coverage under `tests/ansible-agent/`.\n- [ ] 8. Author `skills/ansible-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger language and allowed-tools including `FMT_MODE=*`, `RUN_*`, `CHANGED_FILES=*`, and `TMPDIR_ROOT=*`.\n- [ ] 9. Update `install.sh` for `ansible-agent` SKILLS registration, optional dependency messaging, and AGENTS/CLAUDE snippet wording.\n- [ ] 10. Update `README.md` with ansible-agent table entry and usage examples for `lint`, `syntax`, and `all`.\n- [ ] 11. Run `tests/run-scenarios.sh ansible-agent` with clean/issues/fixture matrix and validate `shellcheck --severity=warning` passes.\n- [ ] 12. Run `ralph validate plan` and fix any plan-format or sequence issues.\n- [ ] 13. Update `.ralph/exploration.md` if any implementation changed documented files, patterns, or schema\n- [ ] 14. All acceptance criteria pass — run `ralph validate work` and confirm PASS\n\n## Architecture Review\n\n### System Design and Component Boundaries\n- The ansible-agent remains a thin orchestration shell around two command steps (`lint`, `syntax`) and is invoked directly by `run-scenarios.sh` fixtures.\n- Shared behavior (`step`, `print_result`, `setup_outdir`, `setup_lock`, `need`, etc.) comes from `lib/x-agent-common.sh`; ansible-agent contributes only domain-specific discovery and command execution.\n- The script boundary is: `run-scenarios.sh` -> ansible-agent -> local CLI tools (`ansible-lint`, `ansible-playbook`) -> filesystem reads + OUTDIR logs.\n- External integration points are minimal: `install.sh` for discoverability and `README.md` for user contract; no runtime service calls.\n\n### Dependency Graph and Coupling\n- Required runtime deps: `ansible-lint` and `ansible-playbook` (`need`-guarded and checked before running steps).\n- Shared lib coupling is critical: changes to `x-agent-common.sh` (especially `need`, `print_result`, lock logic) impact all agents and should remain backward-compatible.\n- Test coupling is through `.env` contract keys consumed by the harness (`SCENARIO_NAME`, `AGENT_SCRIPT`, `EXPECT_EXIT`, `REQUIRED_TOOLS`, `RUN_ARGS`, optional `CHANGED_FILES`).\n- UI coupling via `SKILL.md` and README influences agent discoverability and automation matching quality.\n\n### Data Flow and Bottlenecks\n- Flow: parse CLI/help/flags -> set defaults -> source/discover tool availability -> initialize output dir + lock -> resolve mode/targets -> execute command(s) -> write per-step logs -> print Step/Result/Fix/Overall.\n- CHANGED_FILES affects two branches differently: scope decision for syntax-check targets and skip decision for lint run availability.\n- Primary runtime bottlenecks: recursive YAML discovery (`find`) and per-playbook `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` execution in large repos.\n\n### Scaling Characteristics and Single Points of Failure\n- In monorepos, recursive discovery dominates; prune rules are needed to avoid scanning binaries/node_modules equivalents.\n- Single points of failure: missing required tools (`need` -> exit 2), no playbook discovery (`SKIP` path), malformed YAML causing syntax-check exits, or corrupted lock/temp directory handling.\n- Locking in shared lib avoids concurrent tempdir/log interference but does not prevent command-level contention of ansible tooling.\n\n### Security Architecture\n- No remote auth/API boundaries are introduced.\n- Main attack surface is filesystem path handling and shell command execution; use guarded file filtering and quoting to prevent globbing issues.\n- Running `ansible-lint --fix` locally is mutating by design; CI must force check mode and keep mutation-free behavior.\n\n### Key Architectural Decisions\n\nDecision 1: Playbook discovery model\n- Option A (recommended): recursive `.yml/.yaml` candidate scan + filename heuristics + standard directories + optional `hosts:` filter for syntax candidates.\n- Option B: only `ansible-lint --list`/CLI-discovered paths (simpler, lower control over scoped syntax path mapping).\n- Option C: parse YAML safely with external parsers (`yq`, `python`) to infer playbook structure (accurate but adds dependencies and complexity).\n- Chosen: Option A.\n- Why: deterministic, fast enough for repo-scale fixture patterns, and consistent with existing agents' discovery style.\n- Future impact: this heuristic can be reused for sql/kube-like agents needing mixed path+content rules.\n\nDecision 2: Scope semantics for lint vs syntax under `CHANGED_FILES`\n- Option A (spec-compliant, recommended): syntax is scoped to changed playbook files; lint runs project-wide, but with scoped skip if no relevant YAML changed.\n- Option B: scope lint to changed files only.\n- Option C: scope lint to changed files only for changed-only mode and all files otherwise.\n- Chosen: Option A.\n- Why: matches FR-3/CHANGED behavior and avoids false negatives from partial lint decisions.\n- Future impact: keeps parity with multi-step agents where expensive/cheap steps can have different scope semantics.\n\nDecision 3: FMT_MODE handling\n- Option A (recommended): normalize `FMT_MODE` once in `resolve_fmt_mode` (`auto` -> `fix` local, `check` in CI).\n- Option B: call `ansible-lint --fix` always and skip CI override.\n- Option C: only `check|fix` allowed, no CI override.\n- Chosen: Option A.\n- Why: aligns with go-agent/terra-agent conventions and FR-10.\n- Future impact: low-friction upgrade path for future agents needing local auto-fix semantics.\n\n## Code Quality Planning\n\n### Organization and Module Structure\n- Keep file small and domain-specific (~<200 lines): discovery helpers, mode resolution, two step runners, and one CLI main entrypoint.\n- Group variables in top block: universal knobs, agent knobs, and usage metadata.\n- Keep `usage()` and `collect_playbooks` simple and testable by fixture output.\n\n### DRY Opportunities and Repetition Risk\n- Reuse `print_result` and common timing/cleanup behavior from shared lib instead of custom equivalents.\n- Centralize shared skip branch text in small helper constants if needed (`skip_no_targets`, `skip_no_syntax_targets`) to avoid copy drift.\n- Use one discovery path variable and share filtering operations to prevent duplicated extension checks.\n\n### Error Handling Patterns (Explicit)\n- `need ansible-lint` and `need ansible-playbook` happen before execution to fail fast with code 2.\n- `resolve_fmt_mode` validates unsupported values and exits 2 with actionable message.\n- Discovery functions emit explicit zero-target reasons and return success (no crash), letting caller generate deterministic `SKIP`.\n- Command runners capture command exit codes, dump full output to logs, and only print truncated tails on failures.\n- `main` maps unknown commands to usage + exit 2.\n\n### Technical Debt Controls\n- Avoid clever parsing of YAML; use conservative heuristics with explicit limitations documented in usage and SKILL.\n- Keep command args in arrays where practical; avoid broad global state and deeply nested logic.\n- Add explicit fixture coverage for every branch with `CHANGED_FILES`, `all`, and command-specific invocation.\n- Prefer plain POSIX/Bash 3.2 constructs (no associative arrays/readarray/\n  shell features outside compatibility bounds).\n\n### Engineering Level\n- Engineered enough: explicit branching for scope and modes, not over-abstracted.\n- Avoid over-engineering by not adding config files, caching services, or language parsers unless future iterations need richer semantics.\n\n## Test Strategy\n\n### Coverage Plan\n- Unit-like validation (script-level behavior)\n  - `bash -n` syntax on script and shellcheck severity warning checks in harness.\n- Integration (scenario-based)\n  - `tests/run-scenarios.sh ansible-agent` as the canonical acceptance harness.\n- End-to-end contract checks\n  - Validate `install.sh` registration and README/Skill discoverability by running scenario coverage and grepping for required references.\n\n### Required Edge Cases + Fixture/Assertion Mapping\n1. **Clean pass path**: `tests/ansible-agent/clean/` with valid playbook and required tools. Expect exit 0.\n2. **Issues fail path**: `tests/ansible-agent/issues/` with lint violations. Expect exit 1 and `Fix:` present.\n3. **All command default path**: `RUN_ARGS=\"all\"` on clean and issues fixtures.\n4. **Lint-only command**: `RUN_ARGS=\"lint\"` on clean/issues; confirms command dispatch and `lint` message/fix hint.\n5. **Syntax-only command**: `RUN_ARGS=\"syntax\"` with valid playbook + invalid syntax fixture to verify syntax discovery and aggregate behavior.\n6. **CHANGED_FILES match (lint)**: export one valid playbook in `CHANGED_FILES`; expect lint step execute and overall pass/fail according fixture.\n7. **CHANGED_FILES match (syntax)**: same but with `RUN_ARGS=\"syntax\"`; expect only changed playbooks syntax-checked.\n8. **CHANGED_FILES no-match**: export non-YAML or non-playbook paths; expect `Result: SKIP (no playbooks ... CHANGED_FILES)` and exit 0.\n9. **No playbooks discovered**: fixture with only non-playbook YAML or no YAML files; all commands should `SKIP` gracefully with exit 0.\n10. **FMT_MODE local fix branch**: `FMT_MODE=fix` in clean/issues fixture with local env; ensure command switches to `ansible-lint --fix`.\n11. **CI forces check**: `CI=true FMT_MODE=fix` still executes check mode; fail path should still emit lint SKIP/Fix guidance for check mode.\n12. **Tool failure path (manual)**: invoke script where `ansible-lint` missing to confirm exit 2 (via direct call or environment without tool, since harness marks missing as `SKIP`).\n\n### Failure Modes and Error Path Testing\n- Missing required binary -> exit 2 and clear `Missing required tool` message.\n- Discovery misses files with scoped input -> SKIP path, code 0.\n- ansible-lint returns error -> code 1 and fix hints with exact `/ansible-agent lint` command.\n- ansible-playbook syntax failure -> code 1 with per-path logs and fix hint `/ansible-agent syntax`.\n- Invalid `FMT_MODE` -> code 2 with explicit input guidance.\n\n### Assertion Strength\n- Validate both exit status and branch intent in scenario labels/messages:\n  - `Result: SKIP` vs `Result: PASS/FAIL`\n  - Fix hint content includes exact command path (`/ansible-agent lint`, `/ansible-agent syntax`).\n- For non-empty failure cases, assert full log generation path appears in output.\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\n### N+1 and Command Cost\n- Avoid recomputing discovery for both steps; compute once per run and reuse in `all`.\n- Do not call `find` per playbook. One repository scan + per-target syntax calls is the upper bound.\n- Prefer one `ansible-lint` invocation for lint step vs repeated per-file invocation.\n\n### Memory Usage\n- Store candidate paths in newline-separated strings or Bash arrays only as needed; avoid reading full file contents.\n- Keep full diagnostics in disk logs under `OUTDIR`; avoid loading huge logs into memory.\n\n### Caching Opportunities\n- Cache discovery output for current invocation in environment variable(s) (`PLAYBOOKS`, `CHANGED_PLAYBOOKS`).\n- No cross-run cache; stale discovery state across changing worktrees is riskier than repeated scans.\n\n### Slow/Complex Paths\n- Syntax-check is O(n files) process spawn overhead; this is expected and can be heavy for monorepos.\n- `ansible-lint --fix` can be expensive and mutating; keep this local-only and CI check-only.\n\n### Performance Monitoring\n- If ansible repos become large, prioritize adding prune paths (e.g., `.venv`, `.git`, `.cache`) and optionally role/playbook root detection to limit initial scan depth.\n\n## Decision Log\n\n- Decision: Use `ansible-lint` for lint and `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` for syntax with shared skip semantics\n  - Options considered:\n    - A) Dedicated ansible parser + custom checks.\n    - B) `ansible-lint` + `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` with heuristic discovery.\n    - C) Single command strategy using only `ansible-lint`.\n  - Chosen approach: B.\n  - Implications: clear separation of semantic concerns and predictable error messages across commands.\n\n- Decision: Keep syntax discovery stricter than lint discovery\n  - Options considered:\n    - A) Same target set for lint and syntax.\n    - B) Syntax only runs files with explicit `hosts:` after YAML discovery.\n    - C) Syntax uses lint-only target set.\n  - Chosen approach: B.\n  - Implications: reduces false syntax-check attempts on non-playbook YAML files and lowers avoidable command failures.\n\n- Decision: Keep install/docs as required spec output artifacts, not optional\n  - Options considered:\n    - A) Add script+fixtures only.\n    - B) Add script/fixtures + install/README.\n    - C) Add docs and install updates in separate follow-up.\n  - Chosen approach: B.\n  - Implications: operator and automation discoverability remains accurate immediately after implementation.\n\n## Edge Cases and Risks\n- `CHANGED_FILES` contains spaces: shell word-splitting is path-sensitive; use tested patterns and document limitation.\n- `CHANGED_FILES` includes only role helpers/templates without play-level hosts: syntax may skip while lint still executes.\n- `ansible-lint --fix` may rewrite files; plan for fixture cleanup in manual run scripts if local mutation is tested.\n- Syntax checking on large playbook trees can become slow; keep default `all` command path optimized with cached discovery.\n- `ansible-playbook` on some enterprise collections may attempt optional dependencies; fixture design should avoid unavailable collection imports.\n- `Need` checks can block execution in CI if tools are absent; fixture `REQUIRED_TOOLS` should stay explicit.\n- Script output should preserve Step/Result/Fix/Overall contract even when SKIP paths occur.\n\n## Step-by-Step Implementation Plan\n\n### 1. Contract lock-in and dependency mapping\n**What**: Read spec/standards and finalize exact behavior contract for lint/syntax/CHANGED/FMT_MODE.\n**Why**: Prevents drift from FRs and prior agent conventions.\n**How**:\n- Review `.ralph/specs/09-ansible-agent.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `.ralph/specs/01-02`, and existing scripts (`docker/go/gha` style).\n- Confirm command outputs, SKIP semantics, and required knobs.\n**Edge Cases**:\n- Misaligned FMT_MODE expectation.\n- Confusion around when lint is skipped for scoped input.\n**Tests**: none.\n**Risks**: Early misunderstanding causing repeated fixture churn.\n\n### 2. Build ansible-agent script skeleton and shared-lib wiring\n**What**: Create `skills/ansible-agent/scripts/ansible-agent.sh` with shebang, `set -euo pipefail`, shared lib source, and knob defaults.\n**Why**: Establishes consistent runtime behavior and keeps boilerplate under control.\n**How**:\n- Add `SCRIPT_DIR`, `LIB_DIR`, `source` lines and shebang.\n- Set `RUN_LINT`, `RUN_SYNTAX`, `FMT_MODE`, universal defaults.\n- Keep script executable and named conventionally.\n**Edge Cases**: `source` path errors if script moved; rely on `$(cd ...)` path normalization.\n**Tests**: `shellcheck` catches missing path directives.\n**Risks**: None.\n\n### 3. Implement `resolve_fmt_mode` and discovery helpers\n**What**: Implement CI-aware mode resolver and helper functions for candidate detection.\n**Why**: Centralizes behavior and avoids spread conditionals in runners.\n**How**:\n- `resolve_fmt_mode`: `auto -> local fix, CI check`; invalid mode -> exit 2.\n- `collect_ansible_files`: gather existing `.yml/.yaml` files from `CHANGED_FILES` when set.\n- `discover_playbooks`: recurse for filenames and role/playbook directories per spec; parse only files with `hosts:` for syntax list.\n- Log how many matches were found.\n**Edge Cases**:\n- CHANGED_FILES includes non-existing files.\n- No files found in repo scan.\n- Commented `hosts:` lines not used for syntax selection.\n**Tests**: scoped/ no-match fixtures.\n**Risks**: Overly strict `hosts:` filter skipping valid playbooks with nonstandard layout.\n\n### 4. Implement `run_lint` with project-wide checks and local/CI mode behavior\n**What**: Add lint step using `ansible-lint`.\n**Why**: Core requested linting functionality with fixed/mutating modes.\n**How**:\n- If CHANGED_FILES exists and no `.yml/.yaml` are relevant, emit SKIP.\n- Else call `ansible-lint` with no positional arguments for full project discovery, using `--fix` only in local fix mode.\n- Log output and emit `/ansible-agent lint` fix hint variations for check vs fix failures.\n**Edge Cases**:\n- `ansible-lint --fix` may modify files; run in local branches only.\n- Lint may fail due syntax/parser errors in changed fixtures.\n**Tests**: clean/issues, lint-only mode, FMT_MODE fix and CI check forced path.\n**Risks**: Tool output volume; ensure `MAX_LINES` truncation and full log path.\n\n### 5. Implement `run_syntax` over syntax-discovered targets\n**What**: Add syntax step with `ansible-playbook --syntax-check` per playbook.\n**Why**: Provides execution validation not covered by lint.\n**How**:\n- Iterate over `PLAYBOOKS_FOR_SYNTAX` list, run syntax-check per file into one log.\n- On failures, track aggregate exit and print failing output slices.\n- Return `SKIP` when no matching syntax targets.\n**Edge Cases**:\n- CHANGED_FILES empty + no syntax candidates.\n- One target failing should fail whole step but still run no more files after? (decide fail-fast behavior is per-step only).\n**Tests**: syntax-only pass/fail fixture.\n**Risks**: Additional process overhead in large trees; acceptable with shared cache and path filters.\n\n### 6. Implement command dispatch and all-mode orchestration\n**What**: Add parser for help, fail-fast, and command routing.\n**Why**: Ensures compatibility with existing usage contract.\n**How**:\n- Parse `-h|--help|help` before `need` checks.\n- Parse `--fail-fast` and set `FAIL_FAST`.\n- `all` runs `run_lint` then `run_syntax` based on `RUN_*` with `should_continue`.\n- Unknown command prints usage and exits 2.\n**Edge Cases**:\n- Extra positional args should be ignored or treated as unknown command deterministically.\n**Tests**: invocation matrix for `lint`, `syntax`, `all`, unknown command.\n**Risks**: Shift handling with positional args and default values.\n\n### 7. Add command/behavior fixtures\n**What**: Create `tests/ansible-agent/*` clean/issues plus scoped command scenarios.\n**Why**: Prevents regressions in command and CHANGED_FILES behavior.\n**How**:\n- Create `tests/ansible-agent/clean/` with valid `playbook.yml` and required tools.\n- Create `tests/ansible-agent/issues/` with lint violations.\n- Add at least one scoped-match and one scoped-no-match scenario env using exported `CHANGED_FILES`.\n- Add syntax fixture set for command dispatch and syntax-only failures.\n**Edge Cases**:\n- Ensure variables requiring subprocess visibility are exported.\n- Keep fixtures minimal and deterministic.\n**Tests**: `tests/run-scenarios.sh ansible-agent` must cover these scenarios.\n**Risks**: Overfitting fixtures to one environment or ansible version.\n\n### 8. Add SKILL.md for automation interoperability\n**What**: Create `skills/ansible-agent/SKILL.md` with trigger phrases and allowed-tools.\n**Why**: Required for install/agent integration and allowed tool discovery.\n**How**:\n- Use same structure as other agents.\n- Include `RUN_LINT=*`, `RUN_SYNTAX=*`, `FMT_MODE=*`, `CHANGED_FILES=*`, `MAX_LINES=*`, `KEEP_DIR=*`, `FAIL_FAST=*`, `TMPDIR_ROOT=*`.\n- Mention command forms `lint`, `syntax`, `all` and FMT guidance.\n**Edge Cases**: Missing allowed-tools for `TMPDIR_ROOT` will break automation suggestions.\n**Tests**: Manual read + grep checks.\n**Risks**: Drift if allowed-tools not aligned to runtime knobs.\n\n### 9. Wire install and usage docs\n**What**: Update `install.sh` and `README.md`.\n**Why**: Required for user-facing discoverability and end-user installation path.\n**How**:\n- Add `ansible-agent` to `SKILLS` list and optional dependency check messaging.\n- Extend snippet text in `print_agents_md_snippet` with ansible usage line.\n- Add ansible row in README table and usage examples for lint/syntax commands.\n**Edge Cases**: keep ordering and markdown formatting stable.\n**Tests**: inspect generated snippet text via dry-run path or static diff.\n**Risks**: inconsistent skill naming breaks installer selection.\n\n### 10. Verification and gating\n**What**: Execute required checks and close plan.\n**Why**: Confirms all quality gates before handoff.\n**How**:\n- Run `shellcheck --severity=warning skills/ansible-agent/scripts/ansible-agent.sh lib/x-agent-common.sh tests/run-scenarios.sh`.\n- Run `tests/run-scenarios.sh ansible-agent`.\n- Run `ralph validate plan`.\n- Update `.ralph/exploration.md` with ansible-specific discoveries if files/patterns changed.\n- Run `ralph validate work` and stop on PASS.\n**Edge Cases**: command-specific fixture expectations may fail due path formatting differences.\n**Tests**: explicit commands above.\n**Risks**: validation tooling may require exact checklist ordering and item order.\n","numLines":323,"startLine":1,"totalLines":323}}}
